{
  "texts": [
    "The posterior distribution in a VAE is denoted by q(z | x), where x ∈ X and z ∈ Z, 1) Diffusion Collapse: (for objective 1)We witness diffusion collapse when the posterior distribution becomes overly dispersed:q(z | x) ≈ U(Z) as σ 2 → ∞,(6)where U (Z) denotes the uniform distribution over Z.In this case, the encoder produces highly uncertain latent representations for all inputs.",
    "This can be done by maximizing the KL divergence between N (0, I) (i.e., setting v = 1 in the Equation 12), which can be formulated as:L KL (x) = 1 2 d i=1 -ln σ 2 i -1 + µ 2 i + σ 2 i.",
    "(7)2) Concentration Collapse: (for objective 2) In this scenario, the posterior distribution becomes excessively concentrated, approaching a Dirac delta function:q(z | x) → δ(z -µ 0) as µ, σ 2 → 0, (8)where δ is the Dirac delta function, and µ 0 is typically the mean of the prior distribution.",
    "This collapse results in the encoder mapping all inputs to nearly identical latent representations.",
    "This can be done by minimizing the KL divergence between N (0, diag(c)), where c is some arbitrary small number (i.e., setting v → 0 in theEquation 12), and the KL divergence can be formulated as:L KL (x) = 1 2 d i=1 ln c σ 2 i -1 + µ 2 i + σ 2 i c.(9)Both forms can be derived from the general case, we aim to leverage the divergence measure between q(z|x) and a target distribution p * (z)."
  ]
}